[{"location":"api_reference/#API-Reference","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"api_reference/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"Modules = [ring_model]\nOrder   = [:function, :type]","category":"page"},{"location":"api_reference/#ring_model.initialize_data-Tuple{Int64}","page":"API Reference","title":"ring_model.initialize_data","text":"initialize_data(N::Int; random_seed = 1234)\n\nInitializes the data for the model. The data returns of the following:\n\nregions: A vector of symbols representing the regions in the model.\ngoods: A vector of symbols representing the goods in the model.\nstarting_land_share: A NamedArray with the initial land share for each good.\nweight: A NamedArray with the weight of each good in the utility function.\n\nArguments\n\nN::Int: The number of regions in the model.\n\nKeyword Arguments\n\nrandom_seed::Int = 1234: The random seed to use for the random number generator.\n\nExample\n\nTo create data for 3 regions:\n\n(regions, goods, starting_land_share, weight) = initialize_data(3)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api_reference/#ring_model.ring_mcp-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"ring_model.ring_mcp","text":"ring_mcp(        \n        regions, \n        goods, \n        starting_land_share, \n        weight;\n        initial_labor_endowment = 5000\n    )\n\nConstructs an MCP model of a ring economy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"api_reference/#ring_model.ring_mpsge-NTuple{4, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"ring_model.ring_mpsge","text":"ring_mpsge(\n    regions, \n    goods, \n    starting_land_share, \n    weight;\n    initial_labor_endowment = 5000\n)\n\nConstructs an MPSGE model of a ring economy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#Ring-Model","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"In this write up we am going to assume you have a basic understanding on how to use Julia. If you are not familiar with Julia, we recommend you to go through the official documentation.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"In this tutorial we will guide you through a simple algebraic CGE model using JuMP and the corresponding MPSGE model. The goal is demonstrate the basic concepts of MPSGE modeling, compare it to the algebraic model and show the simplicity/power of the MPSGE syntax. ","category":"page"},{"location":"#Scenario-Introduction","page":"Ring Model","title":"Scenario Introduction","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"Consider a point city, a city with radius 0, at the center of concentric circular files. Denote each ring as r_i so that r_1 is adjancent to the city and r_N is the outermost ring. Assume ring r_i has radius i so that area of ring r_i is given by ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"A(r_i) = pileft(i^2 - (i-1)^2right)","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"Crops are grown in the fields and shipped to the city. For simplicity, assume three crops: corn, wheat and beans. Each crop has a land value share, or the share of land value due to crops rather than labor. These land value shares will be random between 0 and 1. Additionally, each crop has an associated  weight, also random between 0 and 1, that affects its transportation cost. The transportation cost of crop g from region r to the city center is given by the radius of region r times the weight of crop g.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"There are two representative agents in the city, workers and landowners. Both agents live in the central point city and consume 1 unit of each crop. Landowners endow each region with a value equal to the area of the region.Workers endow L units of labor, where L is a model parameter.  ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"We should make note that, as written, this model will be unbalanced. This means the benchmark data will not be consistent with the model equations. In general, this makes modeling significantly more difficult as you are unable to verify your the equations of the model are correct and must rely on your intuition to validate the model structure. MPSGE makes this easier as you can easily verify the model structure without being concerned about equations.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Understanding-the-Model-Structure","page":"Ring Model","title":"Understanding the Model Structure","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"When you being a problem it is important to identify the sectors (markets), commodities (prices), and consumers. The italicized terms are keywords in MPSGE. Let's start with the sectors, or markets, in the model. To identify the sectors ask \"What is being bought and sold and where?\". In this model there are are a large number of markets, but really there are only two distinct sectors: transportation and agriculture. We will discuss each sector in turn.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"All consumers live in the city and consume crops. This means there must be a market transporting each good from each region to the city. This is the transportation sector. The transportation sector is indexed on both regions and crops, meaning there are N cdot G markets in the transportation sector. Each market will buy crops in region r and use labor to transport the crops to the city where they will be sold and city prices.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"The agriculture sector is responsible for growing crops in the regions. This sector is indexed on regions and crops, again there are N cdot G markets in the agriculture sector. Each farm needs to buy labor and land to grow crops and will sell crops at the local price. ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"In our detailing of the sectors, we have identified a number of commodities, or prices: ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"The price of goods in the city\nThe price of labor\nThe price of land\nThe price of goods in each region","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"That turns out to be all the prices. The sectors and commodities are linked, in general you shouldn't have prices that are not present in the sectors, this is possible but we'll discuss the rules later.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"Finally, the problem statement identifies two consumers: workers and landowners. These are not indexed, think of the workers as a pool of labor that is endowed to the markets. This is how we analyze consumers, what do they endow (give) to the market and what do they demand (consume). Both workers and landowners demand goods. Workers endow the market with labor and landowners endow the market with land.","category":"page"},{"location":"#Algebraic-Model","page":"Ring Model","title":"Algebraic Model","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"Before we dive into actual code, lets layout the equations of the model. There are three types of constraints:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"Zero Profit\nMarket Clearance\nIncome Balance","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"Let's start with zero profit. For each sector we must have ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"-textProfit = textCost - textRevenue = 0","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"Let r be a region and g be a good. Consider the transportation[r,g] sector, Figure (1) shows the inputs (costs) and output (revenue) of the sector. The cost function is given by a CES function with elasticity of substitution of 0,","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"    textlabor_pricecdottextdistancercdottextweightg + textregion_good_pricergcdot 1","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"It's a useful exercise to compare the cost function to the inputs of the transportation sector. The revenue is similarly given by ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"    textpricegcdot 1","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"Combining these we have the zero profit condition for the transportation sector,","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"beginalign*\n   textlabor_pricecdottextdistancercdottextweightg + textregion_good_pricerg -  textpriceg perp  texttransportrg\n   endalign*","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"Note that this is a complementarity constraint. ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"The agriculture sector is similar, but with a CES cost function with elasticity of substitution of 1, or Cobb-Douglass. The zero profit condition for the agriculture sector is ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"    textland_pricer^textland_sharegcdottextlabor_price^1-textland_shareg - textregion_good_pricerg  textagriculturerg","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"This brings us to market clearance. Let Pi_s be the profit function for sector s, a_s be the activity level of sector s, H be the consumers, and I_h be the income of consumer h. Then for each commodity p the market clearance condition is given by then for each commodity p the market clearance condition is given by","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"    sum_sin S a_scdotfracpartial Pi_spartial p - sum_hH fracpartial I_hpartial p= 0","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Ring Model","title":"Ring Model","text":"THIS NEEDS SOME CLEAN UP","category":"page"},{"location":"example/#Basic-Example","page":"Basic Example","title":"Basic Example","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"example/","page":"Basic Example","title":"Basic Example","text":"In this example we will set up two models, one in MPSGE and one in MCP. The two models are identical and give the same solutions. ","category":"page"},{"location":"example/","page":"Basic Example","title":"Basic Example","text":"using ring_model\n\nusing MPSGE, JuMP\n\n(regions, goods, starting_land_share, weight) = initialize_data(40)\n\nM = ring_mcp(regions, goods, starting_land_share, weight)\n\nfix(M[:labor_price], 1; force=true)\n\noptimize!(M)\n\nR = ring_mpsge(regions, goods, starting_land_share, weight)\nfix(R[:labor_price],1)\n\nsolve!(R)\n\nvalue.(R[:price])\n\nvalue.(M[:price])","category":"page"}]
